11	In what relation the Apology of Plato stands to the real defence of
12	Socrates there are no means of determining It certainly agrees in tone
13	and character with the description of Xenophon who says in the Memorabilia
14	that Socrates might have been acquitted if in any moderate degree he would
15	have conciliated the favour of the dicasts and who informs us in another
16	passage on the testimony of Hermogenes the friend of Socrates that he
17	had no wish to live and that the divine sign refused to allow him to
18	prepare a defence and also that Socrates himself declared this to be
19	unnecessary on the ground that all his life long he had been preparing
20	against that hour For the speech breathes throughout a spirit of
21	defiance ut non supplex aut reus sed magister aut dominus videretur esse
22	judicum Cic de Orat and the loose and desultory style is an imitation
23	of the accustomed manner in which Socrates spoke in the agora and among
24	the tables of the money changers The allusion in the Crito may perhaps 
25	be adduced as a further evidence of the literal accuracy of some parts 
26	But in the main it must be regarded as the ideal of Socrates according to
27	Plato s conception of him appearing in the greatest and most public scene
28	of his life and in the height of his triumph when he is weakest and yet
29	his mastery over mankind is greatest and his habitual irony acquires a new
30	meaning and a sort of tragic pathos in the face of death The facts of his
31	life are summed up and the features of his character are brought out as if
32	by accident in the course of the defence The conversational manner the
33	seeming want of arrangement the ironical simplicity are found to result
34	in a perfect work of art which is the portrait of Socrates 
36	Yet some of the topics may have been actually used by Socrates and the
37	recollection of his very words may have rung in the ears of his disciple 
38	The Apology of Plato may be compared generally with those speeches of
39	Thucydides in which he has embodied his conception of the lofty character
40	and policy of the great Pericles and which at the same time furnish a
41	commentary on the situation of affairs from the point of view of the
42	historian So in the Apology there is an ideal rather than a literal
43	truth much is said which was not said and is only Plato s view of the
44	situation Plato was not like Xenophon a chronicler of facts he does
45	not appear in any of his writings to have aimed at literal accuracy He is
46	not therefore to be supplemented from the Memorabilia and Symposium of
