365	resignation to the divine will and the certainty that no evil can happen
366	to the good man either in life or death His absolute truthfulness seems
367	to hinder him from asserting positively more than this and he makes no
368	attempt to veil his ignorance in mythology and figures of speech The
369	gentleness of the first part of the speech contrasts with the aggravated 
